        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>To map the full extent of the Vela C ridge, ~90 by ~280 arcseconds, in 3mm continuum emission requires 34 pointings of the 12m array. An angular resolution of 1" will allow us to resolve objects down to 700AU at 700pc. Extrapolating from Herschel data in this region, a minimum peak flux density (of a weak source in the ridge) at 18MJy/beam at 500um equates to ~0.1Jy at 1" resolution at 3mm, assuming ISM dust grains. In order to detect the weak fragmented individual core components of a single clump and the extended emission of the ridge we require a mosaic sensitivity of 20mJy. We will devote two basebands to observing the continuum. Factoring in the spectral line requirements below, a 5-sigma detection, of 100mJy, can then be obtained in 1.27h with the 12m configuration for 34 pointings. The combined time request for the ACA and the 12m array is 4.67 hours in Band 3.

We will use the other two basebands to simultaneously observe the individual core components, and the ridge, at HCO+ (1-0), SiO (2-1) and H13CO+ (1-0). These lines, centred at 89.18674, 86.84522, and 85.75429 GHz, respectively, with a bandwidth of 58.594 MHz will provide a spectral resolution of 0.4km/s. While the science goals are primarily driven by the continuum observations, we would like to obtain a spectral resolution of 0.4km/s  in order to resolve the lines of the individual core fragments. Such narrow lines widths are expected in quiescent cores not yet undergoing star formation. This resolution can be achieved with spectral averaging in each of the lines. Based on experience obtained with H13CO+/HCO+ (1-0) observations in Cygnus X using the Plateau de Bure Interferometer (Csengeri et al. 2010), we estimate that this is sufficient to detect weak lines associated with the individual clump fragments. This spectral line resolution is consistent with that obtained in the 1mm band (band 6) component of this program.

For scheduling purposes, the observations require a RA of 8h.

The combined time required for the 3mm and 1mm observations of this program is 2.27h in the 12m array. The total combined time for both setups and both arrays (12m + ACA) is 9.69h.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
