We will use the two other basebands to simultaneously observe the individual core components, and the ridge, at CO (1-0) and SiO (5-4).  These lines, centred at 230.53339, and 217.10063 GHz, respectively, with a bandwidth of 58.594 MHz will provide a spectral resolution of 0.4km/s. With the science goals driven by the continuum observations, the spectral lines will be obtained with a resolution of ~0.4km/s with spectral averaging, which also matches that achieved at the 3mm band. Such narrow lines widths are expected in quiescent cores not yet undergoing star formation. Based on experience obtained with H13CO+/HCO+ (1-0) observations in Cygnus X using the Plateau de Bure Interferometer (Csengeri et al. 2010), we estimate that this is sufficient to detect weak lines associated with the individual clump fragments.

