    <prp:abstract>High column density filaments, dubbed "ridges", are the preferential sites of high-mass star formation. Such "super filaments" may provide the large reservoir of material from which a high-mass star can accrete. The Vela C ridge, identified by us, provides a unique opportunity to study, at high spatial resolution, the core structure/fragmentation and the dynamics of the closest known ridge. Interestingly, the Vela C ridge displays similar characteristics as the low-mass Serpens South Filament. It is not clear why these two filaments have different (high vs low-mass) star formation histories. We now aim to characterise the cores of the Vela C ridge; through their SED and spectral line tracers such as SiO, HCO+ and CO; to determine their star formation status, and their evolutionary state through age proxies such as the Tbol and Lsubmm. These data will substantially improve our understanding of ridge formation. We also showed that the Vela C ridge likely formed through large-scale converging flows. SiO ALMA observations, with high-resolution column density maps and their probability distribution functions interpreted through numerical simulations, will allow us to test this theory.
</prp:abstract>
